The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Sports | No decision yet on Domenech
                                                                                                                       7                                      No decision yet on Domenech
                      
	Johannesburg: The Fifa stated that no decision has been taken on French coach Raymond Domenechs refusal to shake hands with South Africas Carlos Alberto Parreira after former world champions lost to the hosts. Fifa spokesman Pekka Odriozola says no disciplinary case is active against Domenech.         
	Villa reprieve         
	Johannesburg: David Villa will not face disciplinary action for slapping Emilio Izaguirre during Spains 2-0 win over Honduras after Fifa decided there were no grounds to proceed. The disciplinary committee examined the incident and found no grounds to open a case, a spokesman said during Wednesdays media briefing.         
	Iniesta fit         
	Potchefstroom: Andres Iniesta is set to return for Spains crucial World Cup Group H match against Chile. I trained well, I felt well and I could do everything normally, Iniesta said on Wednesday.         
	Apology         
	Rome: Italian politician Umberto Bossi apologized on Wednesday for his much-criticized remarks that Italy would buy a victory in a crucial World Cup group match against Slovakia. I apologize to the national team, the federal reforms minister told a news agency.         
	Tragic death         
	Seoul: A 20-year-old university student, surnamed Lee, was drowned after he leaped into Seouls Han River with three friends to celebreate South Koreas entry into the second round.         
	Olympic hurdle         
	Johannesburg: South Africas so far successful hosting of the World Cup has increased the prospects to bid for the 2020 Olympics but the biggest hurdle may not come from winning approval abroad. It may come from convincing people at home, recovering from a post-Cup hangover, to spend lavishly again on another global sports party.         
	Back on sale         
	Johannesburg: The Fifa will release 5,000 tickets for the World Cup knockout stage after hosts South Africa and 1998 champions France went out at the group stage. These tickets are coming back from teams that were eliminated such as France and South Africa, Fifa spokesman Pekka Odriozola said Wednesday.         
